# Incident Report Rules & Workflow

This document defines the standardized process followed for triaging, investigating, and documenting every alert in this repository. It ensures each incident report is consistent, repeatable, and defensible.

## 🔄 Workflow Overview

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Alert Triggered] --> B[Initial Triage]
    B --> C[Extract IOCs]
    C --> D[Enrich IOCs<br/>VirusTotal / IP2Location]
    D --> E{Malicious<br/>Indicators<br/>Confirmed?}
    E -->|Yes| F[Classify: True Positive]
    E -->|No| G[Classify: False Positive]
    F --> H[Map to MITRE ATT&CK]
    H --> I[Determine Response Actions]
    I --> J[Contain / Remediate]
    J --> K[Document Recommendations]
    G --> L[Document Rationale for Closure]
    K --> M[Finalize Incident Report]
    L --> M
    M --> N[Report Published to Repository]
```

## 📋 Rule Set

### Rule 1 — Every alert gets triaged before classification
No alert is marked True Positive or False Positive without IOC enrichment (VirusTotal, IP reputation, or equivalent threat intel lookup). Assumptions without evidence are not acceptable.

### Rule 2 — Severity is inherited from the source tool, not reassigned arbitrarily
The severity listed in the report reflects what the SIEM/EDR assigned (e.g., Splunk, Sentinel, Defender). If an analyst disagrees with the tool's severity rating, that disagreement is documented in the **Analysis** section — the original severity is not silently changed.

### Rule 3 — Every IOC must be enriched with at least one external source
Minimum enrichment sources used in this repo:
- **VirusTotal** — reputation and vendor detection count
- **IP2Location / WhoIsMyIP** — geolocation, ASN, hosting provider context

### Rule 4 — MITRE ATT&CK mapping is only applied to confirmed True Positives
False Positives do not receive a technique/tactic mapping, since no adversary behavior was confirmed. Forcing a mapping onto a false positive misrepresents the finding.

### Rule 5 — Every True Positive requires a documented Response Action
At minimum: containment step taken (block IP, isolate host, revoke credential, etc.) and escalation path (if applicable).

### Rule 6 — Every report ends with actionable Recommendations
Recommendations must be specific (e.g., "patch libssh2 to >1.11.1") — not generic advice like "improve security posture."

### Rule 7 — Reports follow the fixed 7-section structure
1. Alert Summary
2. Timeline of Events
3. Indicators of Compromise (IOCs)
4. Analysis
5. MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
6. Response Actions
7. Recommendations

## ✅ Validity Classification Criteria

| Classification | Criteria |
|-----------------|----------|
| **True Positive** | Confirmed malicious indicator (vendor detections, known malicious infrastructure, matched exploit signature/CVE behavior) AND corroborating internal log evidence |
| **False Positive** | No reputation-based evidence of malicious activity AND no suspicious internal behavior (e.g., no repeated failed logins, no anomalous outbound traffic) |
| **Benign/Expected** | Activity confirmed as authorized (e.g., internal scanning tool, approved admin activity) |

